{
  "system": "Photosystem II",
  "mechanism": {
    "kok_cycle": "Photosystem II catalyzes water oxidation at the oxygen-evolving complex (OEC), a Mn4CaO5 cluster coupled to the redox-active tyrosine TyrZ (D1-Tyr161) and the reaction-center chlorophyll pair P680. Upon absorption of a photon, excitation energy is funneled to P680, generating the excited state P680*. Primary charge separation occurs on an ultrafast timescale, yielding the radical pair P680+ Pheo- (phylloquinone/primary acceptor pathway is downstream). Electron transfer proceeds from excited P680* to pheophytin, then to QA, and onward to QB. The oxidizing equivalent at P680+ is relayed via TyrZ, which undergoes proton-coupled electron transfer (PCET) with the OEC. The Kok cycle describes the accumulation of four oxidizing equivalents in the OEC through the S-state sequence S0, S1, S2, S3, and S4. Each flash advances the system by approximately one S-state, although misses and double hits occur in vivo. In the S0 to S1 transition, the cluster is oxidized by one equivalent while proton release is coupled to minimize charge buildup. S1 to S2 and S2 to S3 similarly involve stepwise oxidation of the Mn cluster, with accompanying proton release to the lumen. The S3 state is generally considered the most oxidized stable pre-O2-evolving intermediate, often associated with insertion or reorganization of a water molecule and increased substrate accessibility. The S4 state is transient and highly oxidizing; it is followed by O-O bond formation, O2 release, and reset of the catalyst to S0 or S1 depending on the specific pathway and protonation state. Mechanistically, the O-O bond formation is thought to involve either a nucleophilic attack of a substrate water/hydroxide on an oxo-bridged Mn-oxo species or radical coupling between two oxygen-derived ligands, with substantial evidence supporting a concerted role of PCET, water substrate delivery, and electrostatic tuning by the protein matrix. Proton release is temporally gated across the S-state transitions, with distinct numbers of protons released in different steps, maintaining energetic favorability and limiting back-reaction. TyrZ serves as a redox-active intermediary that couples the one-electron chemistry of P680+ to the multi-electron chemistry of the OEC, mediating fast electron transfer while providing proton relocation that modulates local redox potentials. The overall result is the four-electron oxidation of two water molecules to dioxygen, with storage of reducing power on the acceptor side and stabilization of the catalytic intermediate states by the protein environment.",
    "rubisco_kinetics": "RuBisCO (ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase/oxygenase) catalyzes two competing reactions at the same active site: carboxylation and oxygenation of ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate (RuBP). In the carboxylase reaction, the enediolate form of RuBP reacts with CO2 to form a six-carbon intermediate that hydrates and cleaves into two molecules of 3-phosphoglycerate (3-PGA). In the oxygenase reaction, O2 competes with CO2 for the same enediolate substrate, yielding one molecule of 3-PGA and one molecule of 2-phosphoglycolate, the latter requiring energetically costly recycling via photorespiration. The balance between these reactions is governed by substrate concentrations, temperature, enzyme specificity, and the intrinsic kinetic partitioning of the enediolate intermediate. Key kinetic parameters include kcat for carboxylation, kcat for oxygenation, Km or specificity constants for CO2 and O2, and the specificity factor Sc/o, which quantifies the relative preference for CO2 over O2. RuBisCO must first be activated by carbamylation of an essential lysine residue in the active site, typically stabilized by Mg2+. This carbamylation promotes binding and enolization of RuBP, generating the reactive enediolate intermediate. CO2 acts as the electrophile in carboxylation, whereas O2 participates in the competing oxygenation pathway. The relative rates are influenced by temperature, because increasing temperature generally decreases CO2 solubility more strongly than O2 solubility and can also alter enzyme specificity, thereby favoring oxygenation. The active site architecture constrains stereochemistry and stabilizes reaction intermediates through precise positioning of substrate, metal cofactor, and catalytic residues. From a thermodynamic perspective, carboxylation is productively coupled to the Calvin-Benson cycle, while oxygenation introduces a metabolic penalty through photorespiratory salvage. Thus, RuBisCO is both a highly abundant and imperfect catalyst whose kinetic tradeoffs reflect evolutionary compromise between catalytic speed and discrimination against O2."
  }
}
```

